Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[New Jersey may be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2811015,232.

Horses cannot transmit the virus to humans. However, humans, through carelessness, may allow their horses to acquire the disease. Vaccination protects the horses. It requires 2 vaccines approximately 21 days to 30 days apart to initiate the immunity. In high risk areas, such as near lakes, ponds or in wet years, or if living in coastal areas, horses should have a single repeat injection every 4-6 months. The immunity to Eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) wanes very rapidly.

There has also been an increase in equine West Nile virus (WNV) this year (2014). Again, the mantra is vaccinate, vaccinate, vaccinate. WNV vaccine is in combination with EEE and generally with Western equine encephalitis (WEE) as well. In some areas it is possible to include tetanus in the same combination vaccine. Vaccination is a simple way to protect your horse. - Mod.TG]
